0":"1420–1510","1513":"1513","1435":"1435","1510":"1510","1455":"1455","1477":"1477","1420":"1420","1552":"1552","1550":"1550","about 1443":"omkring 1443","1549":"1549","Much Dewchurch, Herefordshire, England":"Much Dewchurch, Herefordshire, England","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Mynde Park, Herefordshire, England":"Mynde Park, Herefordshire, England"},"nl":{"NN–1550":"–1550","1435–1513":"1435–1513","–1550":"–1550","1477–Female":"1477–Overleden","–1552":"–1552","–Male":"Overleden","1420–1510":"1420–1510","1513":"1513","1435":"1435","1510":"1510","1455":"1455","1477":"1477","1420":"1420","1552":"1552","1550":"1550","about 1443":"circa 1443","1549":"1549","Much Dewchurch, Herefordshire, England":"Much Dewchurch, Herefordshire, England","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Mynde Park, Herefordshire, England":"Mynde Park, Herefordshire, England"},"en":{"NN–1550":"–1550","1435–1513":"1435–1513","–1550":"–1550","1477–Female":"1477–Deceased","–1552":"–1552","–Male":"Deceased","1420–1510":"1420–1510","1513":"1513","1435":"1435","1510":"1510","1455":"1455","1477":"1477","1420":"1420","1552":"1552","1550":"1550","about 1443":"about 1443","1549":"1549","Much Dewchurch, Herefordshire, England":"Much Dewchurch, Herefordshire, England","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Mynde Park, Herefordshire, England":"Mynde Park, Herefordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pye","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (north-West Midlands, Lancashire, Yorkshire, and Norfolk): nickname from Middle English (Old French) <i>pie</i> ‘magpie’, which could be given to someone who wore black and white clothing, had grey-streaked dark hair, or had a loud, chattering voice and impertinent behaviour, or was cunning or sly. The uncomplimentary senses derive from the bird's behavior and are recorded uses of the word in Middle English and early Modern English.","English: occasionally perhaps a topographic or habitational name referring to a house or inn named <i>Pie</i> ‘magpie’. There were two London taverns so named, but whether these gave rise to a hereditary surname is not known. Surnames derived from house and inn signs are rare in English.","English (of Norman origin): nickname from Anglo-Norman French and Middle English <i>pie</i> ‘merciful, compassionate, kind’, a variant of Old French, Anglo-Norman French <i>piu</i>, <i>peu</i>; see   Pew   (2)."],"variants":[{"name":"Pew","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Pugh  .","English: nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>pi(u)</i>, <i>piw</i>, <i>peu</i> ‘holy, pious’, also ‘merciful, kind, compassionate’."]},{"name":"Pyatt","meanings":["English (mainly Staffordshire): nickname either from Middle English <i>piot</i> ‘magpie’ (Old French <i>pïot</i>, a diminutive of Old French <i>pie</i>), commonly used to denote a chattering woman, or alternatively from an unrecorded Middle English <i>pyard</i>, an uncomplimentary term derived from the same Old French word + <i>-(h)ard</i>. Compare   Pye  .","Variant of   Piatt  , a surname of French and Walloon origin.","History: This surname (see 2 above) is listed along with the variant <i>Piatt</i> in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors."]},{"name":"Pie","meanings":["English: variant of   Pye  , in part a cognate of 2 below.","French: nickname from Old French <i>pie</i> ‘magpie’, perhaps given to a talkative person or someone who had a loud, chattering voice.","French (<b>Pié</b>): variant of   Piet   ‘foot’. Compare   Pease   and   Pee  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":23,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705201,"age":117,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"John Pye Of Mynde was born in England as the son of John Pye Of Mynde and Agnes Andrews. He had at least 1 daughter with Elizabeth Whitney. He died in 1550, in Much Dewchurch, Herefordshire, England."},"et":{"NN–1550":"–1550","1435–1513":"1435–1513","–1550":"–1550","1477–Female":"1477–Surnud","–1552":"–1552","–Male":"Surnud","1420–1510":"1420–1510","1513":"1513","1435":"1435","1510":"1510","1455":"1455","1477":"1477","1420":"1420","1552":"1552","1550":"1550","about 1443":"umbes 1443","1549":"1549","Much Dewchurch, Herefordshire, England":"Much Dewchurch, Herefordshire, England","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Mynde Park, Herefordshire, England":"Mynde Park, Herefordshire, England"},"fi":{"NN–1550":"–1550","1435–1513":"1435–1513","–1550":"–1550","1477–Female":"1477–Kuollut","–1552":"–1552","–Male":"Kuollut","1420–1510":"1420–1510","1513":"1513","1435":"1435","1510":"15